iven name in most European languages. Among people with a classical education, it has from time to time been associated with  Virgil's  Aeneid, where it is borne by the sister of  Dido , Queen of Carthage. This Phoenician name may ultimately be of Semitic origin, and thus related to the biblical <i>Anne</i>. However, the connection, if it exists, is indirect rather than direct."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":42,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":115,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Anne d'Anvers was born in 1340, in Waterstock, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, John d'Anvers I, was 45 and her mother, Isabel de la Lea, was 31. She married Sir Thomas Badlington x in 1356, in Oxfordshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in Thame, Oxfordshire, England."},"et":{"1340–":"1340–Surnud","1330–1409":"1330–1409","1340–Female":"1340–Surnud","1345–1387":"1345–1387","1338–Male":"1338–Surnud","1357–1430":"1357–1430","1295–1347":"1295–1347","1310–Female":"1310–Surnud","1330":"1330","1340":"1340","1295":"1295","1382":"138